title: Sina cared about Lusya despite years of bitter. She believed questions will be asked after death and she lived her life accordingly. To us, atheists her advice was to live in a way not to avoid looking at someone’s eyes in future... Ohh, I have to preserve some lobio for winter.
author: Khadija_Ismayil

title: ... answer to Mammadaga (my grandpa who died many years ago).  I remember Grandma Sina and Lusya spending time together,avoiding any talks about ethnic issues and arguing only about whose recipe of lobio is better (I cook both recipes by the way) or what Mammadaga liked the most
author: Khadija_Ismayil

title: My grandfather left her with two children for a well educated Armenian woman. When Baku pogroms started, grandma Sina asked my dad to go and bring Lusya to our house and hosted her for two months until everyone calmed down. She said “if something happens I will have no answer...
author: Khadija_Ismayil

title: ... and we’ll have to live together again. I asked her why she never told us that story, she answered that she didn’t want to load us with unnecessary grievances. She had another personal conflict with an Armenian woman though. ...
author: Khadija_Ismayil

title: My grandma Sona was born in winter 1918. She was a newborn when Gang  led by Armenian commander Andranik burned their house and killed her father.  We have learned about it when conflict started in1988. She told us to behave, because peace will come again and we’ll have to live..
author: Khadija_Ismayil

title: One day I will have to write my family’s history. It is a great story about people who managed to coexist after bloody conflicts and supported each other during bloody days despite personal grievances. The short version is: it is a story of my grandma. Follow thread for the rest
